=== 4.5 The Code: Embedding in Python

Before writing a single line of embedding logic, we name what a matrix _is_.
A matrix is a rows-by-cols grid of numbers.
We store it as a flat vector in row-major order, but nothing above this interface will ever need to know that.

[source,python]
----
include::../../../src/python/common.py[tag=make_matrix]
----

`random_matrix` uses Xavier initialization: it scales the random values by stem:[\sqrt{2/(fan_{in}+fan_{out})}], which keeps activations from exploding or vanishing.

[source,python]
----
include::../../../src/python/common.py[tag=random_matrix]
----

The embedding of token stem:[i] is literally row stem:[i] of the matrix — a table lookup.

[source,python]
----
include::../../../src/python/common.py[tag=embed_token]
----

A sequence of stem:[T] token IDs calls for stem:[T] row lookups stacked into a stem:[[T \times d\]] matrix.

[source,python]
----
include::../../../src/python/common.py[tag=embed_sequence]
----

The dot product stem:[u \cdot v = \sum_i u_i v_i] measures geometric alignment.

